SEPTEMBER 7
WORLD HISTORY
                                                                                                                                 In 1813, the United States is nicknamed Uncle Sam
                                                                                                                              This was derived from Samuel Wilson, a meat packer from Troy, New York who
supplied barrels of beef to the United States Army during the War of 1812.

Wilson stamped the barrels with “U.S.” for the United States.
The soldiers referred to this as “Uncle Sam’s”. Later, the local newspaper developed the story and the name eventually gained national acceptance as nickname for the US federal government

Later, cartoonists Thomas Nast and James Montgomery Flagg developed Uncle Sam’s image as we know today

PRAYER FOCUS
May every symbolic name and image of countries be respected continually by their respective groups. May political cartoonists and artists refrain from making abusive and derogatory artworks.

Names, nicknames and even symbols are often valuable. Even the Lord Jesus had some kind of a nickname, accompanied by a wonderful symbol.

"Therefore the Lord himself will give you[c] a sign: The virgin[d] will conceive and give birth to a son, and[e] will call him Immanuel – Isaiah 7:14
